The first major development lay in the expansion of executive power beyond effective oversight. The president again treated emergency powers as a standing option rather than a last resort. He had already ordered National Guard troops into Memphis under the banner of a \'93Memphis Safe Task Force,\'94 despite local leaders noting crime was at historic lows. This week, that deployment was formalized by executive order and echoed in a draft plan to send 1,000 Louisiana National Guard troops into New Orleans and Baton Rouge for law enforcement work. At the same time, he threatened to declare a national emergency to seize control of Washington DC\'92s police if the city did not cooperate with mass deportations. These moves blurred the line between civilian policing and military force, and between local autonomy and federal command. They signaled that the president saw emergency framing as a routine way to override resistance. That was the point.\
