The same disregard for limits appeared in foreign and economic policy. The administration pressed the Supreme Court to rescue its global tariff regime after a lower court had ruled the tariffs illegal under the emergency economic powers statute. When the appeals court blocked his attempt to fire Federal Reserve governor Lisa Cook, the president went directly to the Supreme Court, asking permission to remove her over unproven mortgage allegations. In parallel, he unilaterally ordered a missile strike on a small boat off Venezuela, killing three people without congressional authorization, and then boasted of the strike without offering evidence. He also signed an order delaying enforcement of the TikTok ban yet again, despite a congressional statute and a Supreme Court ruling requiring the app\'92s shutdown unless sold. In each case, the pattern was the same. When law or institutional design constrained him, he treated those constraints as negotiable suggestions rather than binding rules.\
