A second development was the deepening use of law as a weapon rather than a neutral framework. The Justice Department under Attorney General Pam Bondi explored bringing RICO charges\'97normally reserved for organized crime\'97against protesters, including pro-Palestinian demonstrators. ICE and DOJ charged California healthcare workers with assaulting federal agents after they tried to shield a patient from an immigration arrest in a surgical center. Bondi announced a civil rights investigation into an Office Depot employee who refused to print posters of Charlie Kirk, recasting a private expressive choice as a potential federal offense. The administration pressured federal prosecutors in Virginia to charge New York Attorney General Letitia James with mortgage fraud despite a lack of evidence, and when the US attorney did not deliver, the president prepared to fire him. These actions did not yet amount to a formal rewriting of criminal law, but they showed how existing statutes could be bent toward punishing disfavored speech and opponents. That is how law becomes a weapon.\
\
Immigration enforcement became the central vector for this weaponization. ICE conducted military-style raids across Los Angeles, with masked agents in unmarked vehicles detaining people based on appearance and accent. A Supreme Court ruling cleared the way for warrantless immigration raids, overturning a restraining order that had slowed such operations in California. In Georgia, an ICE raid at a Hyundai plant swept up more than 300 Korean workers, many with valid visas, in what officials later called an operational mistake. Reports described overcrowded detention, lack of basic supplies, and derogatory treatment. A separate court filing detailed inhumane conditions for children at the Dilley family detention center in Texas\'97prolonged confinement, dirty water, sleep deprivation, and emotional abuse\'97allegedly in violation of the Flores settlement. At Angola prison in Louisiana, the notorious \'93Camp J\'94 unit was reopened as an ICE detention site, now called Camp 57, bringing civil detainees into a space long associated with brutality. Together, these actions blurred the line between civil and criminal detention and made immigration status a gateway to harsher treatment and fewer rights. Fear was the through line.\
