The week also saw a structural shift in how citizenship itself was stratified by wealth, origin, and ideology. Texas enacted a law barring many nationals of China, Iran, Russia, and North Korea from buying most real estate, reviving the logic of alien land laws under a new banner. The president signed a proclamation imposing a $100,000 annual fee on H\uc0\u8209 1B visas, a sum that would effectively reserve skilled immigration for the largest and richest employers. On the same day, he created the \'93Gold Card\'94 visa, offering expedited immigrant status to individuals or corporations willing to make million-dollar \'93gifts\'94 to the United States. At the other end of the spectrum, the administration moved to revoke visas from immigrants who had celebrated Charlie Kirk\'92s death, and an immigration judge ordered the deportation of Mahmoud Khalil, a legal permanent resident and activist, for misstatements on his green card form, even as a federal court barred his immediate removal. An appeals court ordered the deportation of Mario Guevara, an Atlanta journalist detained after covering protests, despite his path to residency. These decisions, layered atop warrantless raids and solitary confinement in detention, made clear that access to safety and due process depended increasingly on wealth, nationality, and political speech. Citizenship became tiered.\
