A fourth development was the systematic capture and redirection of administrative agencies away from public protection and toward private and ideological interests. At the Environmental Protection Agency, leaders proposed rescinding the 2009 endangerment finding that greenhouse gases harm human health, thereby undermining the legal basis for federal climate regulation. They also moved to dismantle the agency\'92s research office, cutting staff and capacity. The Justice Department filed briefs seeking to kill Vermont\'92s Climate Superfund Act, which would make major polluters pay for climate damage, arguing that the state law was unconstitutional. At the Department of Labor, officials unveiled nearly 150 deregulatory actions, including a proposal to strip minimum wage and overtime protections from 3.7 million domestic care workers. The same department canceled office leases and cut international labor grants, including $500 million dedicated to fighting child and forced labor abroad. These were not isolated policy tweaks. They were structural changes that shifted the state\'92s posture from guarding workers and the environment to shielding employers and polluters.\
