Public health and science were hit just as hard. Robert F. Kennedy Jr., as health secretary, purged the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices, removing its existing members and installing appointees with little vaccine experience or open skepticism about vaccine safety. He then fired CDC Director Susan Monarez after she resisted demands to pre-approve all vaccine panel recommendations without evidence. The administration canceled a $590 million Moderna contract for a bird flu vaccine and cut funding for mRNA research more broadly. The Pentagon stopped sharing atmospheric and oceanic data with scientists, citing cybersecurity, and the president issued an order on \'93restoring gold standard science\'94 that in practice brought research grants under closer presidential control and targeted diversity initiatives. At the ACIP meeting itself, the new committee first voted to maintain Vaccines for Children coverage of the combined MMRV shot, then reversed itself the next day and eliminated that coverage, with some members revealing they did not understand the program\'92s purpose. The committee narrowly voted against requiring prescriptions for Covid vaccines but emphasized \'93individual-based decision making\'94 and clinician consultation. These moves did not yet ban vaccines, but they weakened the infrastructure that had made them widely and reliably available, especially to poor children. The scaffolding was being stripped away.\
