Labor protections and social safety nets were eroded in parallel. The Labor Department\'92s deregulatory agenda, especially the removal of wage and overtime protections for domestic care workers, shifted bargaining power further toward employers and left millions more dependent on individual negotiation. The president signed a domestic spending bill that cut Medicaid and the Children\'92s Health Insurance Program by more than a trillion dollars over a decade, with the Congressional Budget Office projecting at least 10.5 million people losing coverage, many of them children. Republicans in Congress advanced provisions to delay a ban on PFAS-laden firefighting foam, cut $200 million from cleanup budgets, and lift a moratorium on incinerating the foam, despite known health risks. At the same time, Americans\'92 credit scores were falling at the fastest rate since the Great Recession, as living costs rose and student loan payments resumed. The combined effect was to increase economic precarity while weakening the public tools meant to cushion it. Hardship was treated as acceptable collateral.\
