Information and memory became contested terrain in a more direct way than in earlier weeks. The Justice Department removed from its website a long-standing study showing that far-right extremists had committed more ideologically motivated homicides than any other domestic group. The administration ordered slavery-related exhibits and signs removed from national parks, including a historic photograph of a formerly enslaved man, stripping public spaces of reminders of past oppression. The Education Department announced a partnership with conservative groups to provide programming on patriotism and liberty, aligning civic education with a particular ideological frame. In the media sphere, the president filed a $15 billion defamation suit against the New York Times and its partners, accusing them of acting as a partisan mouthpiece; a federal judge dismissed the complaint as invective-laden and legally deficient, but the suit itself signaled a willingness to use civil courts to intimidate. The goal was to shape what the public could see and know.\
