The most visible clash over media freedom centered on Jimmy Kimmel\'92s late-night show. After Kimmel criticized those exploiting Charlie Kirk\'92s murder, FCC Chair Brendan Carr publicly suggested that ABC\'92s licensees could face regulatory \'93remedies\'94 if they continued to air him. Nexstar, the largest operator of ABC affiliates and a company seeking FCC approval for a merger with Tegna, announced it would stop carrying the show. ABC and its parent, Disney, then suspended Kimmel\'92s program indefinitely. Sinclair Broadcast Group, owned by a Trump ally, stepped in to fill the time slot on many stations with a one-hour tribute to Charlie Kirk and demanded that Kimmel apologize and donate to Kirk\'92s family. Carr later voiced support for Sinclair\'92s demands and launched investigations into NPR, PBS, and media companies engaged in diversity initiatives, while approving a merger that placed a Trump donor as ombudsman at CBS News. House Democrats responded with letters and an investigation into whether the FCC and the White House had abused regulatory power to shape programming, and some called for Carr\'92s resignation. But the structural message to broadcasters was clear. Critical content could bring regulatory pain, while aligned content would find favor.\
