The administration\'92s rhetoric and legal posture toward dissent hardened further. Stephen Miller warned that law enforcement power would be used against political opponents labeled as domestic terrorists. The president announced that he was designating \'93antifa\'94 as a major terrorist organization, despite the absence of legal authority to apply such a label to domestic groups, and his aides explored an executive order invoking treason and sedition statutes against people who identified with antifa or worked in left-leaning nonprofits and voter turnout groups. Attorney General Bondi told employers they had an obligation to fire workers who disparaged Charlie Kirk. Vice President JD Vance used Kirk\'92s own podcast to spread baseless claims about left-wing violence. The president threatened ABC\'92s Jonathan Karl with possible Justice Department targeting for tough questioning and suggested that TV networks with negative coverage might face government punishment or license revocation, even though networks do not hold licenses. These statements did not yet translate into a formal new legal regime, but they shifted the climate. Dissenters were cast as disloyal, dangerous, or corrupt, and the boundaries of acceptable speech narrowed under the shadow of state power.\
