Immigration and protest remained flashpoints where these trends converged. In New York, city comptroller Brad Lander, public advocate Jumaane Williams, and other elected officials were arrested by federal agents while attempting to conduct oversight of detainees at immigration courts. A separate protest outside an ICE intake facility at the Javits building led to the arrest of 71 people, including 11 lawmakers, for blocking access. In Chicago, federal agents in riot gear used teargas and pepper balls to disperse about 100 protesters, including congressional candidates, who were trying to block ICE vehicles. ICE announced that assaulting its officers would be treated as a federal felony and broadened its definition of threats to include actions like filming operations. At the same time, a federal judge in Manhattan ordered improvements to conditions at a federal building where immigrants were held, finding likely First and Fifth Amendment violations, and another judge blocked the deportation of Guatemalan children and upheld temporary protected status for Venezuelans. These rulings showed that parts of the judiciary still acted as a check, but they did so against a backdrop of increasingly militarized enforcement and shrinking space for protest. The clash was stark.\
