Not all movement was in one direction. Courts dismissed the president\'92s defamation suit against the New York Times, blocked his attempt to fire Lisa Cook from the Federal Reserve, ordered improvements in immigrant detention conditions, and halted deportations of vulnerable children and TPS holders. A jury acquitted a Los Angeles protester accused of assaulting a border patrol agent, in part because there was no video evidence to support the charge. A federal judge ordered Rudy Giuliani to pay more than $1.3 million in legal fees tied to his efforts to overturn the 2020 election. In Congress, House Democrats and some Republicans resisted the most extreme measures: a resolution to censure Representative Ilhan Omar failed, a provision that would have allowed the Secretary of State to revoke passports over alleged terrorism support was withdrawn, and lawmakers announced plans for legislation to protect anti-government speech from censorship. These actions mattered. They showed that institutional resistance had not vanished, even if it was often reactive and narrow.\
